r as topoi independent of genre? Do certain representations of demons prevail in pagan, Jewish and Christian circles alike, irrespective of religious background? How do notions of demons function in apocalypses, hymns, hagiographies or texts from healing procedures and what interdependencies of genre and social context can be traced? These questions are analysed from diverse disciplinary perspectives that offer some fresh and surprising answers.  aThe perception of demons in late antiquity was determined by the cultural and religious contexts. Therefore the authors of this volume take into consideration a wide variety of texts stemming from different religious milieus ranging from spells, apocalypses, martyrdom literature to hagiography and focus specifically on the literary aspects of the transformation of the demonic in this period of transition.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aDemonology in literature. 0aDemonology. 0aDevil. 4aAntike /Rezeption. 4aDämonologie. 4aReligionswissenschaft. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aDemonology.  aDemons.  aLate Antiquity.  aTransformation.1 aBremmer, Jan N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElm, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElm, Eva, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrypeou, Emmanouela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartmann, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartmann, Nicole, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLunn-Rockliffe, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarkschies, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVos, Nienk